# Subagent workflow patterns

## When to spawn a subagent
Spawn a subagent (using /spawn or background agent) when:
- A task touches more than 3 files simultaneously
- You need to verify code against standards without bias from writing it
- You need to run tests while continuing to write code
- You need to research a library or API before implementing

## Standard subagent patterns for FinPulse

### Pattern 1: Build + Verify
Step 1 — Implementer subagent: writes the code focused purely on making it work
Step 2 — Reviewer subagent: reviews ONLY against core.mdc and the relevant domain rule. Has not seen the implementation context so reviews with fresh eyes.
Never ask the same agent that wrote code to also verify it meets standards.

### Pattern 2: Parallel ingestion
When adding multiple ingestion sources at once, spawn one subagent per source.
Each subagent works independently. Main agent integrates outputs.

### Pattern 3: Background testing
When implementing a new feature, spawn a background subagent to run existing tests continuously.
Main agent keeps writing. Background agent reports failures in real time.

## After any subagent completes
Update CONTEXT.md with what was built before closing the session.
